  {title: "Part 9", description: "<p>(1921-2014) was a key participant in the Cuban revolution and later a politician and diplomat. After graduating from the University of Havana School of Law in 1943, Hernandez initially worked as a Customs attorney. She was one of the two women, the other being Haydee Santamaria Cuadrado, among the 131 rebels involved in the assault on the Moncada Barracks on July 26, 1953. Sentenced to 7 months in prison, she later assisted Fidel Castro, who remained in prison until 1955, in smuggling out the small portions of text that would be assembled into the manuscript of History Will Absolve Me. Hernandez was with Castro during his Mexican exile and participated in planning the rebel leader&#39;s return to Cuba by the boat Granma in 1956. She joined the fighters with the Third Front under Juan Almeida Bosque. Year after the revolution, Hernandez served as Cuban Ambassador to Vietnam and to Democratic Kampuchea (now again Cambodia) and was a member of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of Cuba.</p>\r\n", duration: "00:15:13", film_id: 1, embed: "<iframe src=\"https://dev-dl-pa.home.nyu.edu/media/clips/TAM-616_ref89_000001/mode/embed/\" height=\"350\" width=\"100%\" allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\"></iframe>", collection_id: 1, slug: "melba-hernandez-rodriguez-del-rey-part-9", thumbnail_file_name: "1430317812.jpg", thumbnail_content_type: "image/jpeg", thumbnail_file_size: 50700, thumbnail_updated_at: "2015-04-30 01:17:14", name: "Melba Hernandez Rodriguez del Rey", transcript_file_name: nil, transcript_content_type: nil, transcript_file_size: nil, transcript_updated_at: nil, year: "", refid: "89_000001"},
