  {title: "Part 1", description: "<p>(1911-2007) was a prominent American lawyer who, with his partner Leonard B. Boudin, defended a generation of American activists on the left. In his 1996 memoir, Unrepentant Leftist, Mr. Rabinowitz explained that from 1942 until the early 1960s, he was a member of the CPUSA. In 1960, the Castro government requested Rabinowitz to represent Cuba in legal cases in the United States. In 1964, he won the Sabbatino case in the US Supreme Court, which upheld Cuba&#39;s sovereign right to nationalize American companies in Cuba. A decade later, Rabinowitz defended Chile&#39;s right to nationalize US firms.</p>\r\n", duration: "00:29:10", film_id: 1, embed: "<iframe src=\"https://dev-dl-pa.home.nyu.edu/media/clips/TAM-616_ref986/mode/embed/\" height=\"350\" width=\"100%\" allowfullscreen=\"\" frameborder=\"0\"></iframe>", collection_id: 1, slug: "victor-rabinowitz-part-1", thumbnail_file_name: "1430317965.jpg", thumbnail_content_type: "image/jpeg", thumbnail_file_size: 43134, thumbnail_updated_at: "2015-04-30 01:17:16", name: "Victor Rabinowitz ", transcript_file_name: nil, transcript_content_type: nil, transcript_file_size: nil, transcript_updated_at: nil, year: "Sep 24, 1996", refid: "986"},
